(3073, 'grgfhg', 'grgfh', 'International Seminar on Geopolitics and BRI in South Asia', NULL, 'Home', 'News & Events', NULL, 1, NULL, NULL, '<h2 style=\"text-align: center;\">International Seminar<br />\r\non<br />\r\nGeopolitics and BRI in South Asia&nbsp;</h2>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nWith the motive to initiate a wider engagement of stakeholders to discuss the implications of BRI in the South Asian region and to disseminate the research findings on “Prospects and Challenges of Nepal-China BRI Agreement”, Centre for Social Inclusion and Federalism (CESIF) organized the \'<strong><em>International Seminar&nbsp;on ‘Geopolitics and BRI in South Asia</em></strong>’ on 23rd December, 2022 at The Everest Hotel, Kathmandu, Nepal. The conference brought together ex-ministers, analysts, academics, diplomats, bureaucrats, politicians, government officials, journalists and experts from South Asian Countries to discuss upon the issues surrounding China’s Belt and Road Initiative (BRI), its geopolitical implications, the fear of perceived “debt-trap diplomacy” of China and other country-specific concern.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>Panel I: BRI and Nepal-China Relations</strong></h2>\r\nThe first panel on ‘BRI and Nepal-China Relations’ brought together former Minister for Foreign Affairs, and current Member of Parliament, Dr. Prakash Sharan Mahat and Former Minister for Foreign Affairs, Mr. Pradeep Gyawali. The session was moderated by Associate Editor at AP1 Television, Ms. Sama Thapa.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/ckfinder/userfiles/images/BRi-pic_1673336695.JPG\" style=\"width: 1374px; height: 866px;\" /><br />\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2><strong>Panel II: Geopolitics and BRI in South Asia</strong></h2>\r\nThe second panel entitled, ‘Geopolitics and BRI in South Asia,’ brought together, Professor Srikanth Kondapalli and Dr. Devendra Kumar from India, Dr. Towfiqul Islam Khan from Bangladesh, Dr. Harim Watson Peiris from Srilanka and Mr. Ajaya Bhadra Khanal from Nepal. The session was moderated by Amb. Vijay Kant Karna.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/ckfinder/userfiles/images/panel2_1673336862.JPG\" />\r\n<h2><br />\r\n<strong>Panel III – Nepal-China BRI Agreement: Sectoral Perspectives</strong></h2>\r\nThe third Panel of the seminar discussed on ‘Nepal-China BRI agreement: Sectoral Perspectives’ which brought together Mr. Purushottam Ojha, the Former Secretary of Ministry of Industry, Commerce and Supplies, Mr. Akhilesh Updhayay, Senior Fellow at IIDS, Dr. Rupak Sapkota, Former Deputy Executive Director at Institute of Foreign Affairs (IFA) and Ms. Shreeya Rana, Senior Program &amp; Research Officer, Policy Entrepreneurs Inc. (PEI) which was moderated by Mr. Amish Raj Mulmi, noted author.<br />\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/ckfinder/userfiles/images/bri-panel3_1673336892.JPG\" style=\"width: 1429px; height: 817px;\" />', NULL, 3072, NULL, NULL, 'CESIF Nepal', '/uploads/banner_image/1673337000_poster.JPG', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2023-01', '2023-01-08', NULL, '1', '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2023-01-09 02:25:34', '2023-01-10 19:09:27'),
(3074, 'pokhara-international-airport-report', 'pokharainternationalairportreport', 'Pokhara International Airport: Research Report', NULL, 'Main', 'Publication', NULL, 3, NULL, NULL, '<h1 style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Pokhara International Airport: Research Report&nbsp;</strong></h1>\r\n\r\n<h2><strong>Abstract</strong></h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Pokhara International Airport is an example of the state driving a development project for the sake of political imagination while muting concerns about commercial viability and corruption. The tension between delivering big showpiece projects and undermining national economic interests by ignoring commercial viability and the costs of corruption is a key challenge facing the current government. This is likely to have significant implications regarding long-term national security interests, corruption, and conflict.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&nbsp;In 1975, the government acquired more than 3,106 ropanies of land in Pokhara, a major tourism hub, for a regional international airport. A detailed project report was prepared in 1989 in association with Japan International Cooperation Agency (JICA), proposing a 2,500-meter-long runway with a terminal and cargo building. At that time the airport was estimated to cost USD 39.6 million.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis paper analyses discrepancies observed while awarding the contract and the outrageous cost structure. It refers to speculated corruption.</p>', NULL, 2671, NULL, NULL, 'Ajaya Bhadra Khanal', '/uploads/banner_image/1673247277_Pkr Airport.jpg', NULL, '1673247277_Pokhara International Airport - Research Report CESIF.pdf', NULL, '2023-01', '2023-01-02', NULL, '1', '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2023-01-09 17:39:37', '2023-01-09 17:39:37'),
(3075, 'china-pays-another-high-profile-visit', 'chinapaysanotherhighprofilevisit', 'China Pays Another High Profile Visit before the November Poll', NULL, 'Main', 'Commentaries', NULL, 7, '<meta charset=\"utf-8\" /><b id=\"docs-internal-guid-87aa4bd3-7fff-8d39-2f9f-f9cc3bf3ba6a\">Li Zhanshu, the Chairman of the Standing Committee of the National People’s Congress arrived in Kathmandu on September 12 leading a 67-member delegation for a 4 - day visit.&nbsp;</b>', NULL, '<p>Li Zhanshu, the Chairman of the Standing Committee of the National People’s Congress <a href=\"https://nepalnews.com/s/nation/chinese-leader-li-completed-the-four-day-visit-to-nepal\">arrived in Kathmandu on September 12 leading a 67-member delegation </a>for a 4-day visit. This marks the third high-level visit from Beijing within a span of a few months after the parliamentary ratification of the Millenium Challenge Corporation Compact last February. Chinese Foreign Minister and State Councillor Wang Yi <a href=\"https://kathmandupost.com/national/2022/03/25/chinese-foreign-minister-wang-arrives-in-kathmandu\">had visited Nepal in March</a>, and Liu Jianchao, the head of the International Liaison Department of the Chinese Communist Party, had visited Nepal in July. During the visit, Li met with President Bidhya Devi Bhandari, Prime Minister Sher Bahadur Deuba, Foreign Minister Agni Prasad Sapkota and other high-level representatives from mainstream political parties of Nepal. The dialogues mainly centred on relevant issues pertaining to Nepal-China relations, with a <a href=\"https://www.thehindu.com/news/international/chinas-third-ranked-leader-li-zhanshu-holds-talks-with-his-nepali-counterparts-sharma-oli-prachanda/article65886248.ece\">focus on the Belt and Road Initiative Agreement</a> signed between the two in 2017.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://english.khabarhub.com/2022/12/272371/\">A six-point MoU</a> was signed<a href=\"https://nepalnews.com/s/nation/6-point-mou-signed-between-nepal-and-china\"> to continue for 5 years </a>by the Honourable Speaker of the Federal Parliament Agni Prasad Sapkota and&nbsp; Li Changshu, Chairman of the National People\'s Congress Standing Committee of the People\'s Republic of China. In the six point agreement, both parties have agreed to focus on strengthening mutual trust, respect each other\'s independence, sovereignty and integrity and support each other’s core interest.&nbsp; Likewise, both sides will try to increase inter-parliamentary exchange and cooperation at all levels through multilateral means. Similarly, both sides will give priority to high-level visits between Nepal and People’ Republic of China, along with exchanges of contacts between the legislatures of both countries. Both parties will promote parliamentary friendly groups to increase their engagement playing roles in strengthening&nbsp; the mutual relationship.The MoU also focuses on the issues relating to strengthening mutual relations under the framework of regional and global organisations and giving importance to facilitating the mutual benefits by means of enhancing inter-connectivity as per agreements including BRI among others.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Frequent high-level visits from China after the parliamentary ratification of the MCC, rejection of the US State Partnership Program (SPP), and just before the federal and provincial elections set to take place in November, have raised many questions. In the past few years, China has increased its engagement and has shown tendencies to interfere in the internal affairs of Nepal. <a href=\"https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/china-commends-nepal-s-decision-not-to-be-part-of-state-partnership-program/\">China openly commended Nepal’s decision to reject SPP</a>, which China had claimed to be a part of the US’s Indo-Pacific Strategy, and had also <a href=\"https://www.nepalitimes.com/here-now/china-lobbying-against-mcc/\">lobbied against the parliamentary ratification of the MCC pact</a>. Further, Liu Jianchao, during his visit, had urged the <a href=\"https://kathmandupost.com/national/2022/07/09/top-level-chinese-visit-piques-curiosity-about-its-purpose\">communist parties of Nepal to come together </a>for the forthcoming polls, reconciling their differences and conflicting interests. Communist Parties in Nepal and CCP share the same ideology, making it easier for China to bolster its influence if and when a communist party runs the Kathmandu administration. <a href=\"https://kathmandupost.com/national/2022/09/12/visiting-chinese-speaker-may-have-speculations-of-left-unity-to-shrug-off\">China was making efforts to push for the communist coalition in Nepal.&nbsp;&nbsp;</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>This time around, significant dialogues were also held on issues surrounding the Belt Road Initiative (BRI), the interconnectivity with Nepal, and the trade prospects. <a href=\"http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2017-05/12/c_136276949.htm\">BRI was introduced back in 2013 by China, and Nepal signed an MOU in 2017</a>. As both the countries have shown less push in implementing the BRI agreement and the infrastructural projects under the initiative have been in limbo for quite a while now. This time, views were exchanged regarding the importance of the implementation of the BRI agreement, however, whether or not the agreement gets implemented is yet to be seen.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Unlike MCC, BRI has loan components, which might pose economic risks for Nepal. China, in recent times,<a href=\"https://english.khabarhub.com/2022/29/265280/\"> has been heavily blamed for the \"debt-trap diplomacy\" </a>as it has been providing developing countries with commercial loans, and in some cases, those countries have failed to pay China in time. Those countries then are made to offer significant concessions to China which has induced skepticisms regarding financial benefits of projects undertaken with Chinese loans. Especially with <a href=\"https://thediplomat.com/2022/08/is-china-to-blame-for-sri-lankas-debt-woes/\">the ongoing economic crisis in Sri Lanka, China has been accused harshly for laying this trap, </a>and as a result, this has led to reduced interest of developing countries in accepting Chinese projects. Thus, the current Deuba administration and some political parties have had apprehensions regarding the financial aspect of the BRI projects.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On t he other side, immediately after Li’s visit, <a href=\"https://nepalnews.com/s/nation/china-to-reopen-2-border-points-for-trade-in-nepal-li-zhanshu\">China partially opened border points, particularly in Rasuwagadhi, </a>and let the containers stuck at the borders for months. China had <a href=\"https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/when-will-the-undeclared-chinese-blockade-end/\">unilaterally imposed a soft embargo</a> on Nepal-China border points under the pretext of Covid-19 pandemic which remained for years. This move to resolve border issues during the high-profile visit could be read as China’s signal of its readiness to solve the unilaterally-imposed border issues.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Given the fact that the federal and provincial polls are nearby, perhaps, this visit could have been waited for a few months. A high-profile visit from a neighbour-superpower at the eve of elections doesn’t carry good diplomatic signals. Despite having a good relationship with China, the rapid change in the nature of Chinese engagements has induced many challenges to Nepal - both in the domestic and diplomatic fronts. Although China’s attempt to push for the communist electoral coalition has failed, it is only likely that China will try to influence Nepal’s internal dynamic even after the November election. Nepal has already been made as a boxing ring in the geopolitical competition among the superpowers. And these types of Chinese approaches might further drag Nepal into the geopolitical tensions in future.&nbsp;</p>', NULL, 2801, NULL, NULL, 'Rasila Dhamala', '/uploads/banner_image/1673254441_Li-Zhanshu.jpg', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-10', '2022-10-21', NULL, '1', '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2023-01-09 19:39:01', '2023-01-11 16:13:18'),
(3076, 'proceesings-report', 'proceesingsreport', 'Proceedings Reports', NULL, 'Main', 'Group', NULL, 3, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 2669, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1', '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2023-01-10 15:02:25', '2023-01-10 22:09:38'),
(3077, 'proceedings-report-military-diplomacy', 'proceedingsreportmilitarydiplomacy', 'Proceedings Report - Federal Level Stakeholders Discussion Seminar on Geopolitics and Role of Military Diplomacy', NULL, 'Main', 'Proceeding Report', NULL, 1, 'Centre for Social Inclusion and Federalism (CESIF) organized a seminar on ‘Geopolitics and Role of Military Diplomacy’ on 29 December, 2022 at Aloft Hotel, Kathmandu, Nepal.', NULL, '<h1 style=\"text-align: center;\">PROCEEDINGS REPORT<br />\r\nOn<br />\r\nSeminar on Geopolitics and Role of Military Diplomacy</h1>\r\n<br />\r\nIn recent times, military diplomacy has played a vital role in Nepal\'s foreign policy, as a tool to promote Nepal’s national interests. Nepal Army has had a long-standing history of cooperation with security agencies of various nations in areas of capacity development and mutual cooperation.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMilitary diplomacy in Nepal is found to have been enhanced over the years, as seen during the ‘unofficial’ blockade days, wherein Nepal Army played a key role not just in minimizing the impact of blockade but also for the negotiation. However, in the past year, Nepal Army has been the pivot in controversies of varied sorts, with NA being dragged even to the parliamentary discourses. These controversies surrounding the Nepal Army, and other challenges pertaining to military diplomacy have brought forth a need to carry out further discussions. With the motive to initiate a wider engagement of stakeholders to discuss the relationship between Nepal’s military diplomacy and heightening geopolitical tension in Nepal as well as to share CESIF’s research findings, Centre for Social Inclusion and Federalism (CESIF) organized a seminar on ‘Geopolitics and Role of Military Diplomacy’ on 29 December, 2022 at Aloft Hotel, Kathmandu, Nepal.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe session brought together distinguished panelists, Dr. Minendra Rijal (Former Minister of Defence), Lt. Gen. Bala Nanda Sharma (Nepal Army), Lt. Gen. Pawan Bahadur Pande (Nepal Army), and Maj. Gen. Purna Silwal (Nepal Army). The objective of the program was to look into expansion in the practices of military diplomacy from past to most recent and also in light of the current geopolitical condition. It also strived to hold a public discussion in the program where experts, former army officials, scholars, researchers and journalists discussed security issues and role of Nepal Army. Through a public discussion the program aimed to accumulate opinion and suggestion to develop policy recommendations for the Government of Nepal, the Nepal Army, and other government officials.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/ckfinder/userfiles/images/1673279841047_1673325073.jpg\" style=\"width: 2592px; height: 979px;\" /><br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe Seminar formally began with the welcoming remarks given by CESIF’s Executive Chairperson, Ambassador Vijay Kant Karna. He described how the session will be focusing on the critical issues regarding Military Diplomacy, Nepal Army’s relation with China, India, USA and other countries through various components. followed by this he mentioned the contribution of Nepal Army in the United Nations Peacekeeping Operations to reflect Nepal’s diplomacy.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAfter his remarks, CESIF\'s Research Fellow Prakriti Shree Adhikary presented the key findings from the research that highlighted Nepal Army’s role in military diplomacy where she provided the timeline from the past to the most recent contribution made by Nepal Army to practice military diplomacy. She mentioned the engagements of Nepal Army in UNPKO, Joint Military Training, Weapon dealing, bilateral relations with countries like India, China and the US and the U.K and, sending Defense Attache to various countries. Furthermore, she also brought the pressing issues of geopolitical competition in Nepal between India, China and the US.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe presentation also included controversy surrounding SPP and how the government of Nepal failed to provide clear information and dragged Nepal Army and the US unnecessarily. In addition to this, she also mentioned the credibility of Nepal Army for initially denying its role in SPP and later, releasing a public statement accepting it did apply for the SPP. At last, she focused on gaps and challenges in practicing military diplomacy to reflect soft power of the country, coordination among the government institutions and Nepal Army etc. Upon the completion of the presentation, the session proceeded with the panel discussion.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis proceedings report aims to summarize the key issues raised in the seminar.<br />\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>Military Diplomacy as a tool to enhance national interest and interrelationship between Nepal Army and Government Bodies</h2>\r\n<br />\r\nMaj. Gen. Purna Silwal reflected upon how the global powers today are coming together to protect their national interest.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nNepal Army, as one of the major tools of the Nepali government, plays a great role in protecting Nepal’s national interest and its future. Nepal Army has played an important role in undesirable events such as floods, insurgencies, earthquake for rescue and relief missions. Nonetheless, it still requires better coordination amongst government institutions and Nepal Army, in order to tackle negative incidents smoothly.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAdding to that, Lt. Gen. Pawan Bahadur Pandey said that, “Nepal Army maintains a cordial relation with the Ministry of Defense as well as the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, however, at times the lack of coordination has been an issue.”<br />\r\n<br />\r\nLt. Gen. Bala Nanda Sharma reflected upon his experience as a Military Attache from 1989 to 1992, when he was puzzled to learn that the Ministry of Foreign Affairs were unable to provide him the required diplomatic assignments and tasks. “The institutions back then were not developed regarding military diplomacy and the assignments that entailed. However, even we were not well acknowledged regarding it.” Incidents like such reflected on how lightly military diplomacy was taken back then. Additionally, he submitted one report per month during his tenure, but later discovered that the officials never examined them. This demonstrates how poorly the institutions coordinated which provided Nepal with little knowledge on military ties with other nations.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nErstwhile Minister of Defense, Dr. Minendra Rijal also shined the light on how important it is to bring back expertise and knowledge acquired from abroad during the peacekeeping missions. Nepal will continue to be prone to disasters and the role of Nepal Army in combating them will be forever paramount as will be the role of military diplomacy in preserving Nepal’s national interest. Thus, the government should also take Nepal Army parallelly with its priorities rather than delving into unwanted polarities.<br />\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>Role of Military Diplomacy in Enhancing Bilateral Relationships</h2>\r\n<br />\r\nLt. Gen. Pawan Bahadur Pandey conveyed how smaller countries are better than larger countries as the former are more tactful to get their point across. He stressed on how crucial joint military exercises, attachments, and bilateral meetings between nations are because they are structured in a way that is not entirely a military component as the joint secretary leads it. He added, “While we have a cordial relation with the Ministry of Defense and the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, I’m unsure if Military Diplomacy is well understood by them. As often, a lot of activities and decisions are conducted in isolation.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAccording to Lt. Gen. Bala Nanda Sharma, it has been difficult for Nepal to maintain a fine balance between its neighbors - two significant economic and military giants. In that context, the importance of military diplomacy has been high.Lt. Gen. Sharma emphasized that in order for the military to maintain the balance, it is first essential to be aware of Nepal\'s geopolitical strategies. He then stated, “the real situation of omnipresence in the world is seriously challenged. How will China’s BRI be negotiated further when we keep changing our positions everytime we change government?”<br />\r\n<br />\r\nLikewise, Maj. Gen. Purna Silwal reflected back on Nepal’s history - how in ancient times, King Prithvi Narayan Shah exercised Military Diplomacy to balance the relations with neighboring countries. He then said, “even in modern times, military aid, military hardware, technology, training, and military alliances were considered to be helpful for bilateral relationships.” Also, in the blockade of 2015, the former Chief of Army Staff (CoAS), Rajendra Chhetri played an important role in removing the blockade within days. He affirmed, “Is it a coincidence or not is up to the imagination.”<br />\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>Failure to Acknowledge Military Diplomacy as a means for conducting foreign policy</h2>\r\n<br />\r\nMaj. Gen. Purna Silwal (Retd) stressed on how there is a hesitation to recognize Military diplomacy as a tool to safeguard our national interest and that only economic diplomacy is prioritized thus far. “Military Diplomacy’s role is extensive, especially in the context of today’s difficult geopolitical dimensions,” he added. Likewise, Lt. Gen. Bala Nanda Sharma shared his experience as an erstwhile USSR now Russia attache. He said, “In my experience as an Attache, I was rather doing tasks that I was not assigned to be doing because the institutions guiding us were not developed enough. I remember, when I was reporting to the Ambassador, he did not even acknowledge my salute.” He then stressed on how words matter in the diplomatic activities; he questioned whether or not we have produced enough diplomats of international standards and the lack of preparedness in undertaking assignments. He reflected back to the blockade by India in 1989 when Nepal itself was unclear about its stance. The 160 embassies were flooded with information and disinformation as presented by the southern neighbor. Even defense attaches stationed in foreign countries were in a dilemma - this reflected poorly on our country’s attitude.<br />\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>Nepal and its role in UN Peacekeeping</h2>\r\n<br />\r\nMaj. Gen Purna Silwal dated back to the time when Nepal got elected to the UN Peacekeeping and has been in the top five ever since. It has been a great platform for Nepal to represent itself as well as to offer possible opportunities of collaboration. As the peacekeepers are deployed in areas where Nepal has no embassies, they can be mobilized in many bilateral and multilateral roles. Thereby, opportunities as such can be used to promote one’s national interest in the international arena.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFormer Minister for Defense and Nepali Congress leader, Dr. Minendra Rijal stated that the Nepal Army has contributed a lot in peacekeeping through UN Peacekeeping Missions, and it should also use those platforms to further national interests. He maintained, ‘The peacekeeping through military diplomacy itself, we can make our presence felt throughout the globe. And that we can bring home the expertise and knowledge we learn internationally.’ He commended the role played by the Nepal Army in rescue and relief operations during varied calamities, insurgencies and emergencies. The audience on how we are in a period where powerful countries are coming closer to confront amongst themselves to protect their interest. Nepal Army as one of its tools of government can play a great role to protect the future in undesirable incidents.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nNepal Army in various events such as Maoist Insurgency, Floods, Earthquake, played a huge role in disaster rescue, relief and response. However, it severely requires better coordination and cooperation on how we can move forward to tackle negative incidents and together achieve national interest.', NULL, 3076, NULL, NULL, 'Prakriti Shree Adhikary', '/uploads/banner_image/1673325360_mil-proceedings.jpg', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2023-01', NULL, NULL, '1', '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2023-01-10 15:21:00', '2023-01-10 22:06:07');
