(3078, 'proceedings-report-BRI-seminar', 'proceedingsreportbriseminar', 'Proceedings Report - International Seminar on Geopolitics and BRI in South Asia', NULL, 'Main', 'Proceeding Report', NULL, 2, 'Centre for Social Inclusion and Federalism (CESIF) organized the International Conference on ‘Geopolitics and BRI in South Asia’ on 23rd December, 2022 at The Everest Hotel, Kathmandu, Nepal.', NULL, '<h1 style=\"text-align: center;\">Proceedings Report<br />\r\non&nbsp;<br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:28px;\">International Seminar on Geopolitics and BRI in South Asia</span><span style=\"font-size:24px;\">&nbsp;</span></h1>\r\n\r\n<h2><br />\r\nContext&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<br />\r\nAs of August 2022, one hundred and forty-nine countries have signed the Memorandum of Understanding (MoU) on China’s Belt and Road Initiative (BRI). In South Asian region, five countries have already joined the Chinese initiative, while it has faced opposition from India right from the beginning. China claims that the BRI is aimed at building infrastructure network connecting Asia with other parts of the world along the overland Silk Road Economic Belt and the 21st Century Maritime Silk Road. In general, BRI has five major components – i) connectivity routes, ii) unimpeded trade, ii) policy coordination, iv) financial integration and v) people-to-people connectivity. Even though China prefers to portray BRI simply as an initiative which would create a “win-win scenario” to all the participating nations. It is speculated that China has also employed this massive initiative to realize its ulterior strategic motives which has led to new geopolitical ramifications in the region. In case of Nepal, it has been five years since the signing of the MoU, however not a single project has been undertaken, nor any provisions implemented.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWith the motive to initiate a wider engagement of stakeholders to discuss the implications of BRI in the South Asian region and to disseminate the research findings on “Prospects and Challenges of Nepal-China BRI Agreement”, Centre for Social Inclusion and Federalism (CESIF) organized the <strong>International Conference on ‘Geopolitics and BRI in South Asia’</strong> on 23rd December, 2022 at The Everest Hotel, Kathmandu, Nepal. The conference brought together ex-ministers, analysts, academics, diplomats, bureaucrats, politicians, government officials, journalists and experts from South Asian Countries to discuss upon the issues surrounding China’s Belt and Road Initiative (BRI), its geopolitical implications, the fear of perceived “debt-trap diplomacy” of China and other country-specific concerns.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe seminar began with Ambassador Vijay Kant Karna addressing the distinguished guests and providing welcome remarks. “Although labelled as an initiative by China, BRI is a global strategic tool. With connectivity links and infrastructure projects spanning as many as one hundred and forty countries, China has aimed to create an alternative economic system with self at the center. This could ultimately pose a challenge to the US-led liberal world order,” said Amb. Karna. Discussing upon varied interest of regional and global actors, he further added that, “the cause of concern isn’t that global and regional actors are seeking to advance their own interest in Nepal. In fact, that’s what all states do. The concern, however, is that, if Nepal will be able find the delicate geopolitical balance while still prioritizing its national interests.”<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe seminar then proceeded with presentation by Ms. Prashanti Poudyal, and by Mr. Sourav Dahal, Research Fellows at CESIF on “Prospects and Challenges of Nepal China BRI Agreement”. The researchers succinctly summarized the findings of research with a focus on political, geopolitical implications of the BRI, contentious provisions included in the MoU – particularly Free Trade Agreement and policy exchange, and explained why the BRI in Nepal has been in limbo for the past five years. They reflected on BRI being China’s global strategy in the ‘guise of connectivity’ to expand its sphere of influence starting from its immediate neighborhood to far beyond. And that the US-Led West saw BRI as a threat to its liberal world order. Since both the US and India have remained firmly opposed to the BRI, its implementation could cause further difficulties for Nepal to tread the thin line of geopolitical balance.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nNotwithstanding, Nepal has not been able to implement the BRI projects and provisions; experts interviewed for CESIF’s research specified varied reasons. Firstly, the lack of preparedness on Nepal’s part, which was seen right from the beginning of signing contentious provisions like the Free Trade Agreement and Policy Exchange in the MoU, to the selection of projects. Secondly, BRI has seen a loss in momentum in the global arena especially in the past few years. Third, Nepal has been especially wary regarding China’s perceived debt trap strategy, which further cautioned Nepali politicians to take a firm stance that BRI projects could not be undertaken with the present financial modality. Political leaders also became cautious to deal with Chinese counterparts after experiences in Pokhara International Airport, Budhi Gandaki Hydropower Project and the infamous Hambantota port fiasco.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nRegarding the Free Trade Agreement, CESIF’s research maintains that FTA would be detrimental to Nepal’s economy due to its already uneven trade ratio with China. Furthermore, as obligated by the WTO, China is already providing 98% of its tariff line for zero-tariff to all LDCs. Nepal however has not been able to utilize that to the fullest, due to various issues like non-tariff barriers among others. Therefore, if Nepal is to move ahead with the FTA with China, there will already be a few spaces with which Nepal can leverage.<br />\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h1>Panel I: BRI and Nepal-China Relations</h1>\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/ckfinder/userfiles/images/BRi-pic_1673330860.JPG\" style=\"width: 1374px; height: 866px;\" /><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe first panel on ‘BRI and Nepal-China Relations’ brought together former Minister for Foreign Affairs, and current Member of Parliament, Dr. Prakash Sharan Mahat and Former Minister for Foreign Affairs, Mr. Pradeep Gyawali. The session was moderated by Associate Editor at AP1 Television, Ms. Sama Thapa.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe session began with Moderator Thapa shedding light on the lack of a proper discourse regarding Nepal\'s Foreign Policy, especially regarding Nepal-China relations. She posed the question to Dr. Mahat regarding the present context of Nepal-China relationship. Dr. Mahat stressed that the SinoNepal relationship is important, especially in regards to BRI. Dr. Mahat highlighted that Nepal lies in between two emerging global powers: China and India, which is an opportunity and as well as a challenge. Dr. Mahat argued that Nepal-China relations is often compared with that of India’s, however, the dynamic of the two can’t be compared due to the geographical differences. Peopleto-people connection as well as trade between China and India are different, as the presence of the Himalayan barrier limits Nepal’s interaction with China. However, that does not hold true in case of India, wherein the engagement is much higher due to the open border in the south. Former Foreign Minister Mr. Gyawali also acknowledged that the relationship between India and China with Nepal is of much significance in a globalized world of today.\r\n<h2>BRI in Nepal and Discussion Before the Agreement</h2>\r\n<br />\r\nDr. Mahat commenced the discussing by referring to the BRI as China\'s mega project, envisioned with the idea of utilizing their own resources for their development. He inferred that Nepal signed the BRI agreement after numerous discussions and meetings in the political and bureaucratic level, however, the initiative has not moved forward. Former Foreign Minister, Mr. Gyawali agreed, and added that the initiatives like BRI would help landlocked and least developing countries like Nepal catch on the global economic trend, as most LDCs haven’t benefitted from the globalization alone.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nDr. Mahat stressed that the implementation of the BRI in Nepal should be strictly based on CostBenefit Analysis. He added that the projects and provisions under BRI should be negotiated so as to reap maximum benefits. Dr. Mahat emphasized that Nepal needs only accept loans, if at all, only for those projects that would ensure return without burdening the economy. Furthermore, Nepal should push for grants instead of loans. However, if China insists on loan, Nepal should ensure that interest rate is at par with that of other multilateral agencies, including the payback period. Mr. Gyawali reflected that ‘we will benefit more if we look at initiatives like BRI as is, without politicizing upon it. It is also important to not let initiatives like MCC and BRI get dragged into unnecessary controversy.’\r\n<h2>FTA and Trans-Himalayan Railway</h2>\r\n<br />\r\nIn the MoU signed between Nepal and China for BRI, there is also a provision under Article II: Areas of Cooperation, III. Trade Connectivity, wherein it states to “conclude the joint feasibility study of China-Nepal Free Trade Agreement within 2017 and if viable, will start negotiations on the Free Trade Agreement (FTA) to further open up markets and expand two-way trade, with a view to achieving a win-win outcome.” When moderator Thapa asked about the possibility of Free Trade Agreement with China, Dr. Mahat, being the chief negotiator for the MoU on BRI, revealed that Nepal had been reluctant to sign the FTA provision; however, Nepal only agreed after a clause was included that stated to first conduct that feasibility study on the FTA, and move forward it with only if viable. He strongly asserted that FTA with China is not possible for now.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFormer Minister Gyawali agreed that FTA with China would be detrimental to Nepal’s economy. He further stressed that in the present context, FTA with any country would not be feasible as Nepal doesn\'t have the production capacity to export. Speaking upon the Trans-Himalayan Railway, which falls under the BRI, Dr. Mahat highlighted that it would be difficult to predict about its future, as the project\'s feasibility study hadn\'t been carried out. He further added that Nepal needs to first ensure its profitability with China before moving forward with it; while India and China would be the primary beneficiary, Nepal would be the secondary.\r\n<h2>Financial Modality of BRI and the Perceived Debt Trap</h2>\r\n<br />\r\nModerator Thapa recalled the erstwhile Prime Minister Sher Bahadur Deuba claiming that Nepal would only move forward with BRI on grants and not on loans. Dr. Mahat stressed that Nepal couldn\'t accept commercial loans from any country and should rather negotiate for grants; thus, the same applied to BRI projects. He reflected upon Nepal\'s increasing debt and stressed that the blend of grant and preferential loans would be most appropriate. The terms and conditions of loan should be at par with multilateral financial institutions, without harsh conditions such as guaranteed return and sourcing of inputs. Former Minister Gyawali too reiterated that Nepal couldn\'t move forward with commercial loans to undertake BRI infrastructure projects; he claimed that there still remains room for negotiation with China to insist on grants or concessional loans. Highlighting that Nepal and China are yet to decide upon the financial modality of the projects, Mr. Gyawali seemed hopeful. While speaking about the perceived debt trap, Former Minister Gyawali gave the example of South American nations who are also under debt, without any investment under the BRI, implying that BRI can’t always be the sole cause of debt trap.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nDr. Mahat underlined upon Nepal\'s weak state institutions to be at fault, stressing the need for stronger institutionalization to deal with loans, grants, and aid. He further added that Nepal needs to do more homework without relying on prejudices; else Nepal will suffer. Geopolitical Tussle in Nepal and its Non-aligned Foreign Policy When discussing the effect of China’s and US’s geopolitical tussle in Nepal by moderator Thapa, Dr. Mahat inferred that Nepal should have a non-aligned foreign policy that should be in accordance with Nepal\'s national interest. Similarly, Former Minister Gyawali admitted the existence of Sino-American rivalry in Nepal, but asked not to view initiatives of these countries, BRI and MCC, through the same lens. These initiatives should be seen from the vantage point of economy centering around Nepal’s national interest.\r\n<h1>Panel II: Geopolitics and BRI in South Asia</h1>\r\n<br />\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/ckfinder/userfiles/images/bri-panel2_1673331342.JPG\" style=\"width: 1381px; height: 859px;\" /><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe second panel entitled, ‘Geopolitics and BRI in South Asia,’ brought together, Professor Srikanth Kondapalli and Dr. Devendra Kumar from India, Dr. Towfiqul Islam Khan from Bangladesh, Dr. Harim Watson Peiris from Srilanka and Mr. Ajaya Bhadra Khanal from Nepal. The session was moderated by Amb. Vijay Kant Karna.\r\n<h2>Covid- 19 Impacting China’s BRI Projects</h2>\r\n<br />\r\nRegarding China’s BRI, Prof. Srikanth Kondapalli spoke about how the mega initiative was disrupted by Covid-19. Due to the Ukrainian conflict, BRI projects have lost momentum in the Eurasian region. While the Eurasian region was one of the major focus of the BRI, crisis in energy and fuel, brought about the Ukrainian conflict, impacted its implementation. The Professor further added that, China may restructure the BRI projects in its summit meeting next year. BRI has been China’s unilateral initiative with bilateral agreements with various countries, this, according to Prof. Kondapalli, is a problem which has limited the BRI’s international legitimacy and acceptance. Had the BRI been pushed as a multilateral initiative, for instance, like Build Back Better World – the US’s response to the BRI, jointly undertaken as a multilateral initiative by all G7 countries, it could garner more acceptance. The failure to do so on China’s part has induced fears and suspicions on China’s intent pertaining to the BRI among its regional and global rivals. The professor, however, expressed that in upcoming meetings, there are chances for the China to be more flexible regarding other controversial conditions of BRI.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nRegarding the GSI (Global Security Initiative) and GDI (Global Development Initiative), Professor Kondapalli stated that the concept still remains unclear. He mentioned that it is difficult to understand the agenda behind these initiatives as China has time and again brought new concepts and modified them into something else, for example, it brought the concept of “peaceful rise of China” in 2002 which was later modified into the Peace and Development. He added, ‘Thus, not much can be said about such initiatives yet.’ To conclude, the Professor suggested it is still not clear if initiatives like GSI, and GDI is brought to replace the BRI projects.\r\n<h2>Failure of BRI projects in Bangladesh</h2>\r\n<br />\r\nRegarding the implementation of BRI project in Bangladesh, Dr. Towfiqul Islam Khan highlighted two terms: i) time overrun and ii) cost overrun. He said that the reason behind the failure of projects is mostly because the projects can’t be completed in the proposed time and which ultimately increases the cost of the project. He also highlighted that due to the over estimation of the cost, the building of infrastructures becomes expensive in Bangladesh than in any other countries. Dr. Khan mentioned that Bangladesh is a labor surplus, densely populated country with a population density of more than 1200 per square km. With conditions as such, he mentioned that it is challenging to implement BRI project in Bangladesh as it comes with higher chances of labor law violations. He said that the BRI projects are not clear about all its underlying terms and conditions, which causes doubt and confusion. He further added that, the lack of transparency and confusion in terms and conditions don’t just hold true for the projects under BRI, but is also an issue in other projects with various regional neighbors. Hence, Dr. Khan concluded with the statement that the problem with lending countries is that they want to be super power, “but they should not only prioritize the conditions that serves them but should also be considerate of the conditions that serves the recipient countries,” he concluded.\r\n<h2>Economic Crisis in Sri Lanka</h2>\r\n<br />\r\nDr. Harim Watson Peiris shared that the roles played by the political leaders in Sri Lanka was not in interest of general public but rather in the interest of the leaders themselves. Dr. Peiris shared that it was not just the commercial loan component that led to the downfall of the Sri Lankan economy but was the combination of the White Elephant. He also added that the governance system was already corrupted which further exacerbated the matter. Hence, as a result, Sri Lanka’s democratic institutions failed causing the economic collapse. It eventually led to a public outrage which in turn forced the leaders out of their offices. While taking about the transparency in the foreign policy and issues of negotiations between countries, Dr. Peiris shared that China is now becoming an important global lender in the national finances of even democratic South Asian countries. He added that China’s involvement can be seen clearly in the situation of Sri Lanka. But on the other hand, he also mentioned that China is slow to recognize the principle of popular support and public consent as they have never been a part of Chinese system.\r\n<h2>China’s Surprising Interest towards Nepal</h2>\r\n<br />\r\nMr. Ajaya Bhadra Khanal expressed that after President Xi Jinping took office, China’s approach to Nepal has significantly changed. He added that the day before President Xi visited Nepal in 2019, he had sent a signed article in Nepali media, known as the blue-print for the Nepal-China relationship. He also added that the blueprint contained four-point idea – i) deepen strategic communication, ii) broaden practical co-operation, iii) expand people to people exchanges and iv) enhance security co-operation. Mr. Khanal questioned the first point on deepening strategic communications and what it may entail. He further added that the blueprint also talked about the need to maintain high level exchanges and political mutual support on issues concerning each other’s core interest. He predicted that Nepal may have more exchanges on governance and development as that is the major point that comes up repeatedly during the statements by Chinese leaders including Chinese Ambassadors to Nepal.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMr. Khanal, also spoke about China seeking to become the preeminent power not only in Asia but also in the world. He mentioned about Chinese Foreign Minister and State Councillor Wang Yi’s visit to Nepal that emphasized upon three things: i) China will make concerted efforts with Nepal to find a suitable model of governance conducive to Nepal’s stability and economic growth, ii) China supports Nepal in pursuing independent domestic and foreign policy, and iii) China supports in furthering Nepal’s participation in the BRI. He questioned China’s intent regarding the first point. Mr. Khanal, finally, suggested that China is looking to increase its the closeness with Nepal so as to discourage Nepal’s closeness with the US.\r\n<h2>Tension in India-China Relations Regarding India-China relationship</h2>\r\n<br />\r\nDr. Devendra Kumar expressed that the key point that holds the two together is their economic bond. He said that China and India improved their relationship in the early 80’s. He further added that the Indian government was in dilemma whether to improve their economic relations or the border issue first. Dr. Kumar also added that after the withdrawal of the Soviet forces from Afghanistan which led to China’s shift in focus towards Pakistan. To prevent regional tensions, the Indian government then improved economic relations with China. Regarding the boundary issues, Dr. Kumar assessed that India is waiting for Chinese reaction on whether or not it reduces the tension alongside the border. As it is unsure how China will be taking this economic relationship further, Dr. Kumar said that India is taking initiatives by signing IndiaJapan partnership in Asia-Africa corridor, India’s partnership with Russia in building North South Corridor and Maritime corridor which was announced in 2019, and India has also joined IndoPacific Economic Framework. Dr. Kumar concluded with the statement that in order to learn more about India-China relations, we need to look at how China behaves and what actions India will take after that.<br />\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h1>Panel III – Nepal-China BRI Agreement: Sectoral Perspectives</h1>\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/ckfinder/userfiles/images/bri-panel3_1673331992.JPG\" style=\"width: 1429px; height: 817px;\" /><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe third Panel of the seminar discussed on ‘Nepal-China BRI agreement: Sectoral Perspectives’ which brought together Mr. Purushottam Ojha, the Former Secretary of Ministry of Industry, Commerce and Supplies, Mr. Akhilesh Updhayay, Senior Fellow at IIDS, Dr. Rupak Sapkota, Former Deputy Executive Director at Institute of Foreign Affairs (IFA) and Ms. Shreeya Rana, Senior Program &amp; Research Officer, Policy Entrepreneurs Inc. (PEI) which was moderated by Mr. Amish Raj Mulmi, noted author.\r\n<h2>Changing Geopolitical Context and Trends of BRI</h2>\r\n<br />\r\nMr. Amish Raj Mulmi began the discussion by highlighting the BRI as an instrument of economic engagement with impacts at the governance and political level. He spoke upon the economic viability brought forth by the BRI projects, recent slow-down on BRI from both Nepal and China, and the viability of BRI 2.0. Mr. Akhilesh Upadhayay shared that BRI is perceived as a potential win by the Global South due to its promises of large-scale infrastructural investment. As we have learned from the Sri Lankan economic crisis, and given that the BRI projects have not begun as of yet, Nepal is in a sweet spot as it can still negotiate a better deal. ‘In a globalized world of today, we can benefit from stronger ties with China. Now is the time to use our leadership to negotiate better deals with China regarding the BRI,’ he added. He provided the example of how the Marshall Plan brought economic ties and prosperity in Europe, which in turn benefited the US.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSimilarly, BRI can bring economic prosperity in South Asia, which means China needs us as much as we need it. However, dealing with China comes with its own strings attached, as it often expects political support in return, sometimes in controversial issues, like Taiwan and Tibet. Since that goes against Nepal’s fundamentals of democracy, our leadership becomes all the more important to tread diplomatically with China. He also inferred an emerging trend of countries getting debt-trapped by China, with the flashing example of Sri Lanka. However, it becomes important to remember that Sri Lanka already had a dire financial condition coupled with a corrupt government, and that the Chinese loans only played its role in the economy’s deterioration. He pointed out that ‘we often expect for better diplomatic ties to be with no strings attached, however, in diplomatic ties, there is no free lunch.’ As a small state, we need to nurture a rulebased regime, with transparency and capable people in the government, to negotiate the best deal possible with our regional and global neighbors.\r\n<h2>Chinese Perspective in Nepal-China BRI Agreement</h2>\r\n<br />\r\nDr. Rupak Sapkota began by shedding light on the geopolitical landscape of how China has perceived the world and vice versa, especially after the launch of the BRI in 2013. He mentioned that China is seen as a threat to the liberal world order led by the US. Nevertheless, countries have benefitted by perceiving China as an opportunity for their growth and thereby engaging in better ties with it. With BRI, the US fears that China may become a regional and in turn a global hegemon, which explains the one-sided narrative today. He reiterated that China is working on policy adjustment and restructuring of the BRI with changing global dynamics. He mentioned that about 140 countries have already signed BRI MoU as of 2022 which shows that China has expanded BRI over the globe as evidenced by Nepal being featured in the second International Forum of BRI in 2019 even though it was not in the first time in 2017. He added that although the BRI agreement has the same template of MoUs for all countries, the policy documents and financial modality are different for individual countries. In recent times, the financial modality was found to have been restructured as seen in Sri Lanka. Chinese foreign direct investments have increased after 2020, and some countries have seen success stories whilst others are still cautious about money borrowed from China following the situation of Sri Lanka. He shared the recent policy adjustment of China being more generous as some countries got concession on loans, interest rates and received longer repayment time upon negotiation. He referred to Prof. Kondapalli’s argument on China planning to organise the third international forum of BRI next year which in turn is speculated to bring more changes to the BRI. He reflected back on Nepal being triggered following the blockade of 2015 after the promulgation of Constitution of Nepal and Nepal’s plans to increase economic ties with China. In the current geopolitical situation, growing convergence of India and USA is the foremost challenge for the BRI. With the recent trend in BRI, he suggested that we need to work upon the financial modality covering the mechanism and implementation plan of BRI after learning from our regional neighbors to negotiate better with China.\r\n<h2>Trade Dynamics in Nepal-China BRI agreement</h2>\r\n<br />\r\nMr. Purushottam Ojha began his viewpoints by stating that Nepal signed the BRI in 2017 with components of the Free Trade Agreement (FTA) inclusive. With decreasing exports and increasing imports in Nepal with China, FTA is bound to be detrimental for the Nepali economy. Although moving forward with the Free Trade Agreement would nonetheless enhance benefits on both sides of Nepal and China, we need to consider factors such as supply of goods and Non-Tariff Barriers. He focused on how despite having several trade agreements with China since 1981, challenges persist when it comes to its implementation. He highlighted how, as per the commitment to the World Trade Organization, China is mandated to provide Duty-Free-Quota-Free to 96% of its tariff line to all Least Developed Countries. Meaning Nepal can export with zero tariff on 4700 goods, which Nepal has yet to reap benefits of due to hindrances such as Non-Tariff Barriers, among others. He delved into the fact that we have failed to implement trade agreements because our border points are not being operated post-COVID-19, and four out of six border points lack access to road services. Despite signing transport agreements in the past and the introduction of the Trans Himalayan Multidimensional Connectivity Network, we still lack transport connectivity at the border points itself. On the part of the government, we have yet to push for the implementation of the connectivity agreements despite having diplomatic missions stationed in five places in China and consultation mechanisms openly mentioned in trade agreements. He stressed that we need to enhance the dialogues and consultation mechanisms to discuss the implementation openly. He suggested that the government and business communities to sit together to discuss on how Nepal and China can develop coherence in trade.\r\n<h2>China in Nepal’s Infrastructure Sector and its Political Economic Perspective</h2>\r\n<br />\r\nMs. Shreeya Rana began her viewpoints with China changing its aid perspective to concessional loans with Nepal still wanting grants. She stressed that we need to understand the shift in paradigm and modality of aid over time. She reflected on 2016/17, when despite negotiations and trade-offs in aid, Nepal did not have much to lose and aid was not driven by market conditions as it is now. She opined that not only China, but every other country is looking at its economic opportunity. She added that China is often portrayed as a predatory donor with its vested interests, while other donor countries too have tight conditionalities. She implied that while we are expecting more investment from China, we need to be careful on where our market is going, further adding that India wouldn’t buy the energy produced with Chinese investment. While discussing Chinese projects, she gave the example of Pokhara International Airport, whose financial viability was questioned upon its completion. She mentioned that we need to be clear regarding any projects by Chinese containing the elements of connectivity that are packaged as BRI projects. \"We need to stop being bugged by the old narrative of geopolitical dilemma and move forward with more practical considerations\" she concluded.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMr. Updhayay added that we should carefully approach China for investments and not randomly select projects based on our own political preferences. He also mentioned that we need to change our mindsets regarding development, as highways and concrete skyscrapers are not the only yardstick of development.\r\n<h2>Conclusion: Making the Best of the Opportunity</h2>\r\n<br />\r\nThe seminar brought forth arguments regarding the merits and demerits of the Nepal-China BRI agreement. If BRI is researched well, Nepal can use those learnings to utilize the initiative for its infrastructural development. As a nation sandwiched between two emerging giants, opportunities to established economic ties with the two will prove beneficial. Stakeholders also agreed that some projects under the BRI were proposed without much homework, but also that it is possible to negotiate them with China for a mutually beneficial agreement. However, Nepal should also be careful regarding China’s controversial loan component. Furthermore, Nepal should use its leadership to re-negotiate with China regarding contentious provisions such as the Free Trade Agreement and Policy Exchange. A better deal can still strike, stakeholders opined. Nepal has had a historic tie with China, undertakings like BRI has the potential to deepen the ties whilst bolstering Nepal’s economy', NULL, 3076, NULL, NULL, 'Prashanti Poudyal, Sourav Dahal', '/uploads/banner_image/1673332205_bri-proceeding.jpg', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2023-01', '2023-01-02', NULL, '1', '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2023-01-10 17:15:05', '2023-01-10 17:52:33'),
(3079, 'proceedings-report-chinese-engagements-Pokhara', 'proceedingsreportchineseengagementspokhara', 'Proceedings Report - Provincial Level Stakeholders\' Discussion Seminar on Chinese Engagement and BRI in Nepal', NULL, 'Main', 'Proceeding Report', NULL, 3, 'Centre for Social Inclusion and Federalism (CESIF) organised a Provincial Level Stakeholders’ discussion (seminar) in collaboration with the Department of Political Science, Prithvi Narayan Campus on “<strong>Chinese Engagements and BRI in Nepal</strong>” on December 10, 2020 at Hotel Crown Himalayas, Pokhara.', NULL, '<h1 style=\"text-align: center;\">Proceedings Report<br />\r\non<br />\r\nChinese Engagements and BRI in Nepal</h1>\r\n<br />\r\nChina’s BRI (Belt and Road Initiative), to which Nepal became a signatory in 2017, is an ambitious infrastructure development project unveiled by the Chinese government in 2013 with the aim of connecting countries along the historic Silk Road. Nine infrastructural projects in Nepal are proposed under the BRI agreement – however, these projects have been in limbo. Apart from BRI, the Chinese engagements have been massively increased in the later years with a visible geopolitical ramification in Nepal. While many perceive the increased Chinese interest in infrastructure projects in Nepal as an opportunity to fulfil its goal of development, its critical implications in Nepal’s political economy cannot be undermined.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nChinese funded projects implemented by Chinese entities in Nepal, more often than not, have faced issues of time and cost overrun among others. Among the large-scale China funded infrastructure projects in Nepal, Pokhara International Airport serves as a prime example. There exist increasing concerns on political and economic front regarding it. Further development in BRI is contingent upon China’s foreign policy under Xi Jinping’s third term presidency as well as the orientation and priorities of the new coalition government in Nepal.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis necessitates a thorough discussion on prospects and challenges of BRI implementation in Nepal along with social, (geo)political, economic and environmental implications of Chinese engagements (including Chinese funded and contracted projects). In this regard, the Centre for Social Inclusion and Federalism (CESIF) organised a Provincial Level Stakeholders’ discussion (seminar) in collaboration with the Department of Political Science, Prithvi Narayan Campus on “<strong>Chinese Engagements and BRI in Nepal</strong>” on December 10, 2020 at Hotel Crown, Pokhara.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis seminar brought together politicians, bureaucrats, intellectuals, economists, infrastructural experts, businessmen, representatives of the tourism industry and journalists among others to share the initial findings of CESIF’s research on Prospects and Challenges of the Nepal-China BRI Agreement, as well as to discuss the challenges and opportunities of the BRI projects at the Sub-national level. The seminar began with a Welcome note by Mr. Uma Baral, Professor at the Prithivi Narayan Campus, followed by key remarks from CESIF’s Executive Chair, Amb. Vijay Kant Karna on the themes and the context the BRI agreement.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/ckfinder/userfiles/images/IMG_20221210_095342_1673334100.jpg\" /><br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe seminar proceeded with a presentation on CESIF’s research on The Prospects and Challenges of the Nepal-China BRI Agreement and its major findings by Ms. Prashanti Poudyal, Researcher at CESIF. Ms. Poudyal succinctly summarized the findings of research with a focus on political, geopolitical implications of the BRI, contentious provisions included in the MoU – particularly Free Trade Agreement and policy exchange, and explained why the BRI in Nepal has been in limbo for the past five years. She reflected on BRI being China’s global strategy in the ‘guise of connectivity’ to expand its sphere of influence starting from its immediate neighborhood to far beyond. And that the US-Led West saw BRI as a threat to its liberal world order. Since both the US and India have remained firmly opposed to the BRI, its implementation could cause further difficulties for Nepal to tread the thin line of geopolitical balance. Notwithstanding, Nepal has not been able to implement the BRI projects and provisions; experts interviewed for CESIF’s research specified varied reasons.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nFirstly, the lack of preparedness on Nepal’s part, which was seen right from the beginning of signing contentious provisions like the Free Trade Agreement and Policy Exchange in the MoU, to the selection of projects. Secondly, BRI has seen a loss in momentum in the global arena especially in the past few years. Third, Nepal has been especially wary regarding China’s perceived debt trap strategy, which further cautioned Nepali politicians to take a firm stance that BRI projects could not be undertaken with the present financial modality. Political leaders also became cautious to deal with Chinese counterparts after experiences in Pokhara International Airport, Budhi Gandaki Hydropower Project and the infamous Hambantota port fiasco.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nRegarding the Free Trade Agreement, CESIF’s research maintains that FTA would be detrimental to Nepal’s economy due to its already uneven trade ratio with China. Furthermore, as obligated by the WTO, China is already providing 98% of its tariff line for zero-tariff to all LDCs. Nepal however has not been able to utilize that to the fullest, due to various issues like non-tariff barriers among others. Therefore, if Nepal is to move ahead with the FTA with China, there will already be a few spaces with which Nepal can leverage.\r\n<h2>BRI as a Global Strategy</h2>\r\nAmb. Vijay Kant Karna began by stressing upon the strategic aspect of the global initiatives like the BRI and MCC - on how they all have vested interest. After establishing itself as an emerging economy, China then envisioned to become a regional and global power, which gave birth to BRI as a global strategy. President Xi Jinping’s visit in October 2019 highlighted China’s interest in Nepal. Post pandemic and Xi’s rise to the third term, China began restructuring BRI, especially the loan component under it; many speculate that BRI 2.0 will be China’s new endeavor.\r\n\r\n<h2>BRI and Infrastructures</h2>\r\nMr. Amish Raj Mulmi reflected upon how BRI brought enthusiasm in Nepal with its big infrastructural undertakings. However, Nepal had not taken into account the political influence BRI would bring alongside. He said, ‘we need to learn from the experiences of Sri Lanka, which took a commercial loan with high interest rate, which was bound to further cripple its declining economy. Today, 19.6% of Sri Lanka’s foreign debt is Chinese loans, which is a high percentage.’ Now, post pandemic, China is found to be trying to restructure BRI as can be seen in its reduction in frivolous lending since 2019. Mulmi further added that the Nepali economy is in a dire situation with debts accounting 21% of its GDP. Thus, Nepal should tread carefully before accepting further loans, especially if it comes with high interest rate.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMulmi also added that BRI should be looked in its profitability as China has invested more than 30 billion dollars in South Asia. Such a large scale investment can prove beneficial for Nepal too. The major question is how will Nepal maintain a fine geopolitical balance with both China and India. Since the Chinese Communist Party has had good relations with the communist parties of Nepal, will the relation between the two nations be determined by the party that leads the parliament next? Further, he asked, will the interaction between the two neighbors be party-to-party or government-to-government?<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOne of the attendees, Mr. Bishwas Shankar Palikhe mentioned that there has been no proper study conducted for the BRI and its long-term impacts to Nepal. He further added that the construction of the Pokhara International Airport took longer than planned which further escalated its cost. Mr. Ananda Raj Mulmi, former President of the FNCCI, clarified that the Pokhara International Airport is not part of BRI, however the fact that Pokhara, Nijgadh and Lumbini International Airports are all being constructed within the radius of 1000 Km makes little sense. However, Pokhara International Airport helps to understand the nature of Chinese investment in Nepal. He mentioned that the state should learn from the experiences of the Hambantota Port in Sri Lanka, Railway in Kenya and road projects in Laos, to understand if we can pull of a project with China, who are known for managing and undertaking the entire planning to implementing phase, by involving local collaborators only a little. Roads like Kodari-to-Kathmandu was built from the money China earned from its exports to Nepal; likewise, Mahendra Bridge was constructed by a Chinese company using Nepal’s public funds; ‘thus, we need to be careful on how our resources are used,’ he added.\r\n<h2>Ties between China and Pokhara</h2>\r\nMr. Ananda Raj Mulmi further stressed that Pokhara has played an integral part in NepalChina relations. Pokhara held a special relation with Tibet and thereby have had a long affiliation with the present-day China. Both India and China have funded for projects in Pokhara as it has been significant. In fact, Pokhara-to-Baglung highway as well as Pokharato-Kathmandu highway were constructed strategically. Mr. Lekhnath Bhattarai, a professor at the Prithivi Narayan Campus, mentioned that since BRI has more of a loan component instead of grants, it can help create ownership over the projects. Furthermore, to make BRI effective, industries and the business sector should be involved one way or the other, he opined.\r\n\r\n<h2>Change in Global Geopolitics and the Role of Political parties</h2>\r\nToday there exists an increasing geopolitical competition between the USA and China.&nbsp;Mr. Lekhnath Pandey shared that by 2050, China will be ahead of all in terms of economy. Which makes it all the more important for Nepal to have a balanced relation with both of its neighbours. Mr. Than Bahadur Chhetri mentioned that our political parties now do not have a common national ideology; he opined that our foreign affairs dealings have been on an ad hoc basis which does not quite send out a good message. He echoed that now political parties should have a common ideology with one foot on politics and another on economics.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMs. Bidhya Bhattarai, Member of the House of Representative from Kaski - 2, began by sharing that there hasn’t particularly been much discussion in the parliament regarding BRI neither in the media. Furthermore, responsible parties, particularly signatories, were neither questioned afterwards. She further added that we don’t have political discussions on grants and loans like we do on political benefits and alliances. Referring to our political scenario as in a building phase, she opined that it will take time for Nepali politics to mature and we mustn’t lose hope. For now, we must brace ourselves for a multi-polar world with our foreign policies treading carefully. Appreciating CESIF’s research presented, she added that agreements with foreign countries, such as BRI, should be well studied in order for us all to learn from.\r\n<h2>Conclusion: Making the Best of the Opportunity</h2>\r\nStakeholders then discussed about making the best of the opportunity provided with the BRI. Certainly, BRI must be discussed and researched well, however, it can also be a great opportunity for a country like Nepal that wants to expand its infrastructural endeavours. As a nation sandwiched between two emerging giants, opportunities to established economic ties with the two will prove beneficial. Stakeholders also agreed that some projects under the BRI were proposed without much homework, but also that it is possible to still be aware of them and negotiate with China for a mutually beneficial agreement. Nepal has had a historic tie with China, undertakings like BRI has the potential to deepen the ties whilst bolstering Nepal’s economy.', NULL, 3076, NULL, NULL, 'Prashanti Poudyal, Sourav Dahal', '/uploads/banner_image/1673334201_pkr-proceedings.jpg', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2023-01', '2023-01-02', NULL, '1', '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2023-01-10 17:48:21', '2023-01-10 17:53:39'),
(3080, 'pokhara-seminar-2022', 'pokharaseminar2022', 'Provincial Level Stakeholders\' Discussion Seminar', NULL, 'Home', 'News & Events', NULL, 2, 'Chinese Engagements and BRI in Nepal&nbsp;', NULL, '<h2 style=\"text-align: center;\">Provincial Level Stakeholders’ Discussion Seminar<br />\r\non<br />\r\n“<em><strong>Chinese Engagements and BRI in Nepal</strong></em>”</h2>\r\n\r\n<h4 style=\"text-align: center;\">In Collaboration with the Department of Political Science, Prithvi Narayan Campus, Pokhara</h4>\r\n<br />\r\nChinese funded projects implemented by Chinese entities in Nepal, more often than not, have faced issues of time and cost overrun among others. Among the large-scale China funded infrastructure projects in Nepal, Pokhara International Airport serves as a prime example. There exist increasing concerns on political and economic front regarding it. Further development in BRI is contingent upon China’s foreign policy under Xi Jinping’s third term presidency as well as the orientation and priorities of the new coalition government in Nepal.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis necessitates a thorough discussion on prospects and challenges of BRI implementation in Nepal along with social, (geo)political, economic and environmental implications of Chinese engagements (including Chinese funded and contracted projects). In this regard, the Centre for Social Inclusion and Federalism (CESIF) organised a Provincial Level Stakeholders’ discussion (seminar) in collaboration with the Department of Political Science, Prithvi Narayan Campus on “<em><strong>Chinese Engagements and BRI in Nepal</strong></em>” on December 10, 2020 at Hotel Crown Himalayas, Pokhara.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis seminar brought together politicians, bureaucrats, intellectuals, economists, infrastructural experts, businessmen, representatives of the Pokhara International Airport, representatives of the tourism industry and journalists among others to share the initial findings of CESIF’s research on Prospects and Challenges of the Nepal-China BRI Agreement, as well as to discuss the challenges and opportunities of the BRI projects at the Sub-national level.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAmb. Vijay Kant Karna - Executive Chairperson of CESIF, Mr. Uma Baral - Profesor at the Pritvi Narayan Campus, Mr. Than Bahadur Chhetri -&nbsp; Head of Dept. of Political Science Prithvi Narayan Campus, Mr. Amish Raj Mulmi - author of \'<em>All Roads Lead North - Nepal\'s Turn to China</em>\',&nbsp;Mr. Ananda Raj Mulmi - former President of the FNCCI,&nbsp;Mr. Lekhnath Bhattarai - Professor at the Prithivi Narayan Campus,&nbsp;Ms. Bidhya Bhattarai, Member of the House of Representative from Kaski, Mr. Bishwas Shankar Palikhe among others were the notable speakers of the discussion.&nbsp;<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&nbsp;', NULL, 3072, NULL, NULL, 'CESIF Nepal', '/uploads/banner_image/1673338164_pkr cover.JPG', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2022-12', '2022-12-12', NULL, '1', '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2023-01-10 18:54:24', '2023-01-10 19:09:52'),
(3081, 'military-diplomacy-2022', 'militarydiplomacy2022', 'Federal Level Stakeholders\' Discussion Seminar', NULL, 'Home', 'News & Events', NULL, 3, NULL, NULL, '<h2 style=\"text-align: center;\">Federal Level Stakeholders’ Discussion Seminar<br />\r\non<br />\r\nGeopolitics and Role of Military Diplomacy</h2>\r\n<br />\r\nMilitary diplomacy in Nepal is found to have been enhanced over the years, as seen during the ‘unofficial’ blockade days, wherein Nepal Army played a key role not just in minimizing the impact of blockade but also for the negotiation. However, in the past year, Nepal Army has been the pivot in controversies of varied sorts, with NA being dragged even to the parliamentary discourses. These controversies surrounding the Nepal Army, and other challenges pertaining to military diplomacy have brought forth a need to carry out further discussions.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWith the motive to initiate a wider engagement of stakeholders to discuss the relationship between Nepal’s military diplomacy and heightening geopolitical tension in Nepal as well as to share CESIF’s research findings, Centre for Social Inclusion and Federalism (CESIF) organized a seminar on ‘<em><strong>Geopolitics and Role of Military Diplomacy</strong></em>’ on 29 December, 2022 at Aloft Hotel, Kathmandu, Nepal. The session brought together distinguished panelists, Dr. Minendra Rijal (Former Minister of Defence), Lt. Gen. Bala Nanda Sharma (Nepal Army), Lt. Gen. Pawan Bahadur Pande (Nepal Army), and Maj. Gen. Purna Silwal (Nepal Army).<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/ckfinder/userfiles/images/mil2_1673338821.JPG\" style=\"width: 1291px; height: 822px;\" /><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<img alt=\"\" src=\"/ckfinder/userfiles/images/mil1_1673338791.JPG\" /><br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe objective of the program was to look into expansion in the practices of military diplomacy from past to most recent and also in light of the current geopolitical condition. It also strived to hold a public discussion in the program where experts, former army officials, scholars, researchers and journalists discussed security issues and role of Nepal Army. Through a public discussion the program aimed to accumulate opinion and suggestion to develop policy recommendations for the Government of Nepal, the Nepal Army, and other government officials.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&nbsp;', NULL, 3072, NULL, NULL, 'CESIF Nepal', '/uploads/banner_image/1673338884_1673279841047.jpg', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2023-01', '2023-01-02', NULL, '1', '0', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2023-01-10 19:06:24', '2023-01-10 19:07:47');
